(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Simulation Games"
  :chapter-number      15
  :title               "The Simulation IS the Game"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "simulation-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + physics-simulation-emergent"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :provenance          ((:authored-by "Engineer") (:date "2026-07-16"))
  :prose
"There are games you win. There are games you finish. And there are
games that just KEEP GOING, whose delight is not the ending but the
watching. A city sim. A garden sim. An ecosystem where sheep and
wolves and grass find each other in a slow dance of populations. A
sandbox where the rules exist but no goal does.

Some of the most beloved games ever made are of this kind. They give
you tools and a world and let you play in it. The score is your
attention. The victory is a beautiful arrangement.

This chapter builds an ecosystem. Grass grows via cellular-automaton-
like rules. Sheep eat grass and reproduce. Wolves eat sheep and
reproduce. Populations rise and fall — a classic Lotka-Volterra
oscillation, emerging without any predator-prey math written down.
We let the user intervene — seed grass, remove a wolf, watch what
ripples. The user is not scoring points; they are learning cause and
effect at scale. The chapter closes with Cortex holding the
ecosystem's history so long-running sessions can be resumed.

---

## 15.1 The world

A grid. Each cell is grass-empty, grass-growing, or grass-full.
Grass-empty becomes grass-growing after a while; grass-growing
becomes grass-full after more time; grass-full stays until eaten.

```scheme
(define ECO-COLS 60)
(define ECO-ROWS 40)

(define (init-ecosystem)
  (grid-init ECO-COLS ECO-ROWS)
  ;; Fill 30% with grass-full, rest empty
  (let loop-c ((c 0))
    (when (< c ECO-COLS)
      (let loop-r ((r 0))
        (when (< r ECO-ROWS)
          (when (< (random) 0.3)
            (grid-set! c r 'grass-full))
          (loop-r (+ r 1))))
      (loop-c (+ c 1)))))
```

Grass rule: each frame, some fraction of empty cells regrow. Each
grass-growing cell has a chance to mature.

```scheme
(define GRASS-REGROW-PROB 0.005)
(define GRASS-MATURE-PROB 0.05)

(define (step-grass)
  (let loop-c ((c 0))
    (when (< c ECO-COLS)
      (let loop-r ((r 0))
        (when (< r ECO-ROWS)
          (case (grid-ref c r)
            ((grass-empty)
             (when (< (random) GRASS-REGROW-PROB)
               (grid-set! c r 'grass-growing)))
            ((grass-growing)
             (when (< (random) GRASS-MATURE-PROB)
               (grid-set! c r 'grass-full))))
          (loop-r (+ r 1))))
      (loop-c (+ c 1)))))
```

## 15.2 Sheep

```scheme
(define (spawn-sheep x y)
  (let ((s (world/spawn 'sheep x y)))
    (entity/mass!      s 1.0)
    (entity/max-speed! s 1.2)
    (ai/wander         s 1.0)
    (ai/bb-set!        s 'energy 20)
    (ai/bb-set!        s 'age 0)
    s))

(define SHEEP-EAT-ENERGY 5)
(define SHEEP-REPRODUCE-THRESHOLD 40)
(define SHEEP-MOVE-ENERGY-COST 0.02)

(define (step-sheep sheep)
  ;; Consume energy as it moves
  (ai/bb-set! sheep 'energy
    (- (ai/bb-get sheep 'energy) SHEEP-MOVE-ENERGY-COST))
  ;; If standing on grass-full, eat it
  (let* ((pos (entity/pos sheep))
         (c   (quotient (car pos) 8))
         (r   (quotient (cdr pos) 8)))
    (when (and (>= c 0) (< c ECO-COLS)
               (>= r 0) (< r ECO-ROWS)
               (eq? (grid-ref c r) 'grass-full))
      (grid-set! c r 'grass-empty)
      (ai/bb-set! sheep 'energy
        (+ (ai/bb-get sheep 'energy) SHEEP-EAT-ENERGY))))
  ;; Reproduce if enough energy
  (when (> (ai/bb-get sheep 'energy) SHEEP-REPRODUCE-THRESHOLD)
    (ai/bb-set! sheep 'energy (/ (ai/bb-get sheep 'energy) 2))
    (spawn-sheep (entity/x sheep) (entity/y sheep)))
  ;; Die if out of energy
  (when (<= (ai/bb-get sheep 'energy) 0)
    (entity/despawn! sheep)))
```

The sheep wanders. If it's on grass, it eats. If it has enough
energy, it reproduces (halving its own energy, spawning a child with
the other half). If out of energy, it dies. Simple rules.

## 15.3 Wolves

```scheme
(define (spawn-wolf x y)
  (let ((w (world/spawn 'wolf x y)))
    (entity/mass!      w 1.5)
    (entity/max-speed! w 1.5)
    (ai/wander         w 0.7)
    (ai/bb-set!        w 'energy 40)
    (ai/pursue         w (world/nearest 'sheep x y))
    w))

(define WOLF-EAT-ENERGY 20)
(define WOLF-REPRODUCE-THRESHOLD 80)
(define WOLF-MOVE-ENERGY-COST 0.05)

(define (step-wolf wolf)
  (ai/bb-set! wolf 'energy
    (- (ai/bb-get wolf 'energy) WOLF-MOVE-ENERGY-COST))
  ;; Update pursuit to always chase nearest sheep
  (let ((prey (world/nearest 'sheep (entity/x wolf) (entity/y wolf))))
    (when prey
      (ai/pursue wolf prey)
      ;; If close enough, eat
      (when (< (geom/distance (entity/pos wolf) (entity/pos prey)) 6)
        (entity/despawn! prey)
        (ai/bb-set! wolf 'energy
          (+ (ai/bb-get wolf 'energy) WOLF-EAT-ENERGY)))))
  (when (> (ai/bb-get wolf 'energy) WOLF-REPRODUCE-THRESHOLD)
    (ai/bb-set! wolf 'energy (/ (ai/bb-get wolf 'energy) 2))
    (spawn-wolf (entity/x wolf) (entity/y wolf)))
  (when (<= (ai/bb-get wolf 'energy) 0)
    (entity/despawn! wolf)))
```

Wolves chase the nearest sheep, eat when close, reproduce with
excess energy, die when out.

## 15.4 The frame loop

```scheme
(define pop-history '())

(init-ecosystem)
(repeat 40 (lambda () (spawn-sheep (* (random) 480) (* (random) 320))))
(repeat 10 (lambda () (spawn-wolf  (* (random) 480) (* (random) 320))))

(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (world/step)
    (step-grass)
    (world/each 'sheep step-sheep)
    (world/each 'wolf  step-wolf)
    (when (= 0 (modulo t 30))
      (set! pop-history
        (cons (list t (world/count 'sheep) (world/count 'wolf))
              pop-history)))
    ;; Paint
    (paint-grass)
    (world/each 'sheep (lambda (s)
      (paint-circle (entity/x s) (entity/y s) 3 white)))
    (world/each 'wolf (lambda (w)
      (paint-circle (entity/x w) (entity/y w) 4 red)))
    (when (= 0 (modulo t 60))
      (plot-populations pop-history))))
```

`paint-grass` renders grass cells in shades of green. Sheep are
white dots, wolves red. Population history plots over time.

## 15.5 Lotka-Volterra emerges

Watch what happens. Grass grows plentiful. Sheep multiply, eating
grass. Wolves multiply, eating sheep. Sheep decline. Wolves,
running out of prey, decline. Grass regrows. Sheep rebound. Wolves
rebound. Repeat.

The two populations trace an oscillation in phase space (plot sheep
count on x-axis, wolves on y-axis, watch a closed loop form). This
is the Lotka-Volterra predator-prey model, emerging from micro-rules
that never mention 'oscillation.' The oscillation is a macroscopic
consequence of the local dynamics.

Sometimes the oscillation is stable — a limit cycle. Sometimes one
species goes extinct — the other soon follows if it was prey-
dependent. The outcome depends on initial numbers, on grass regrow
rate, on reproduction thresholds.

## 15.6 The user intervenes

```scheme
;; Click a cell: seed grass there.
(on-input 'mouse-click
  (lambda (x y)
    (grid-set! (quotient x 8) (quotient y 8) 'grass-full)))

;; Press 's' to add sheep.
(on-input 'key-s
  (lambda ()
    (let ((m (input/mouse-pos)))
      (spawn-sheep (car m) (cdr m)))))

;; Press 'w' to add wolf.
(on-input 'key-w
  (lambda ()
    (let ((m (input/mouse-pos)))
      (spawn-wolf (car m) (cdr m)))))

;; Press 'r' to remove nearest wolf.
(on-input 'key-r
  (lambda ()
    (let ((m (input/mouse-pos)))
      (let ((w (world/nearest 'wolf (car m) (cdr m))))
        (when w (entity/despawn! w))))))
```

Now the user can perturb. Add a wolf; watch the sheep population
crash. Remove all wolves; watch sheep explode until grass runs out.
Seed grass in a corner; watch a stable sub-population form there.
The user is not scoring; they are learning ecology by touch.

## 15.7 Cortex holds the ecosystem across sessions

```scheme
;; Save state on exit.
(on-exit
  (lambda ()
    (cortex/write 'ecosystem-state
      (list :grass  (grid-snapshot)
            :sheep  (world/snapshot 'sheep)
            :wolf   (world/snapshot 'wolf)
            :time   (frame)))))

;; Load on startup.
(on-startup
  (lambda ()
    (let ((saved (cortex/read 'ecosystem-state)))
      (if saved
          (begin
            (grid-restore! (cdr (assoc :grass saved)))
            (world/restore! (cdr (assoc :sheep saved)))
            (world/restore! (cdr (assoc :wolf  saved))))
          (init-ecosystem)))))
```

Now the ecosystem persists. The user can leave for a week, come
back, and pick up their world. The sheep they left in the north-east
corner are still there, maybe with more of their kind. The wolves
they removed are still absent.

This is what turns a simulation into a garden. It is yours; it
persists; you tend it.

---

## 15.8 The four routing patterns

**Composition.** The ecosystem is composed of grass rules + sheep
rules + wolf rules + intervention handlers. Each is independent.
Add fire, add drought, add hunters — each composes cleanly.

**Orchestration.** The frame loop orchestrates: step physics, step
grass, step sheep, step wolves, sample populations, paint. Longer
orchestration: 'run for 10000 frames, take snapshots every 100 frames,
save all snapshots to Cortex, allow later playback.'

**In-routing.** Mouse click routes to grass-seeder. Key press routes
to species-adder or -remover. Sheep-eats-grass event (proximity
check) routes to grid-set + energy update. Wolf-eats-sheep event
routes to sheep-despawn + wolf energy update.

**Routing.** Sheep and wolf positions route to framebuffer. Grass
grid routes to green-shade fill. Population history routes to a plot
plus to Cortex ('sheep peak was 187 at frame 2400'). User
interventions route to a log so we can replay the session and
attribute changes to actions.

---

## 15.9 Common desktop tasks

An operator running a hydroponic-farm consulting shop asked the runtime:
'if I add nitrogen at rate R and remove plants at rate P, will the
tank stabilize?' The predator-prey math is close enough as a first
approximation. Model nitrogen as grass, algae as sheep, plant-
harvesting as a wolf pulse. The oscillations and stable points give
the operator a first-pass answer they can refine.

## 15.10 Try this

1. Remove all wolves. What happens to sheep? What happens after
   sheep boom?
2. Halve grass regrowth. Does the ecosystem still cycle?
3. Give sheep more energy per grass. Does population plateau higher?
4. Add a second predator (bear) that eats wolves. Watch three-species
   dynamics.
5. Track the phase-space trajectory (sheep count vs wolf count over
   time). Is it a closed loop?

## 15.11 Pitfalls

**Extinction.** Too few of one species and the ecosystem collapses
irreversibly. This is realistic — real ecosystems have similar
tipping points — but for a play sim you may want to seed a rescue.

**Cost.** N sheep * M wolves nearest-neighbor queries is O(N*M).
Use `world/spatial-index` for larger populations.

**Cell size.** If cells are too small, sheep don't reliably eat
grass they walk over. If too large, grass looks blocky. 8-pixel
cells with 3-pixel sheep is a decent compromise.

